,"Of, Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1198–after 1225":"1198–after 1225","1198–1225":"1198–1225","1198–1226":"1198–1226","1215–1260":"1215–1260","1221–1267":"1221–1267","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1180–1258":"1180–1258","1173–Female":"1173–Deceased","1198":"1198","1197":"1197","1173":"1173","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","after 1225":"after 1225","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","ABT 1221":"about 1221","1267":"1267","1221":"1221","Woodham Walter, Essex, England":"Woodham Walter, Essex, England","England":"England","Of, Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzWalter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English, Irish: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name   Walter  , ‘son of  <i>Walter</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitzwater","meanings":["Irish: altered form of <b>Fitzwalter</b>, a patronymic from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   Walter  , meaning ‘son of <i>Walter</i>’.","History: This is the name of a family of Norman origin, descended from Godfrey, Count of Brionne (died <i>c.</i> 1010). Godfrey's grandson, Richard FitzGilbert, accompanied William the Conqueror and was made Lord of Clare. His great-grandson was Robert FitzWalter, one of the barons who guaranteed the Magna Carta in 1215."]},{"name":"Walter","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), German, Dutch, Polish, Swedish, and Danish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This personal name was introduced into England both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Amphyllis","type":"FIRST","meanings":["English: Loquacious."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":17,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":26,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Amphyllis FitzWalter was born in 1198, in Woodham Walter, Essex, England, her father, 